title: For Sale:  Marlin 336CS 30-30
postcontent:
bought this gun used at a gun store last year with the intent of hunting. at the time i bought it, looked brand new. my hunting friend moved away, and i lost interest.
i shot about one and half boxes of ammo through it. needs to be sighted in.
very slight scratching on the foregrip, scratches have been stained so at least theyre not noticeable. gives the gun character anyway.

comes with 10 or 11 rounds of ammo to get you started and sighted in.

has been shot so little, that the loading door isnt even scratched up from loading in rounds.

appears to be drilled and tapped from the factory, so you can put a scope on it.

this is the CS model, meaning i think its a Carbine, and it has a Safety

most people like the winchester as a lever action, but i can tell you the marlin is a superior shooter. the hooded front sight makes sighting easier. it ejects to the side instead of the top, so you can put a scope on it. the lever action workings are much simpler and more durable and feel solid compared to the winchester. the stock feels alot nicer on your shoulder and in your hands.

this really is a wonderful rifle, and i would just keep it and never shoot it, but she should be used be someone who will appreciate her.

included is a cable gun lock, with which some inventiveness, i was able to secure around the rifle to keep kids or room mates from actuating the lever and discharging the rifle.

open to trades for other firearms only. price is firm. cash only. if the ad is up, i still have the rifle. will only sell to Vermont resident.

title: For Trade:  1790 Pheasant Art Piece
postcontent:
You are looking at a rare piece of history here (Pheasant Shooting). This is a 1790 Brittish Aquatint that has three artist's combined works in one. The original piece was painted by George Morland English Painter (1763-1804) with permission it was Etched by Thomas Rowlandson English Painter and Caricaturist (1756-1827) and Aquatinted by Samuel Alken Sr. a Brittish Sporting Artist (1756-1815). 

This was issued as a Sporting Series in 1790 and published by J. Harris and T. Merle. This was acertained by Ralph Richardson's Chronological Catalogue of Etchings and Engravings showing their years of publication (all were published in London). Reference: http://www.sterlingtimes.org/morland_catalogue2.htm
The above link could also help reflect its value as well.

The artwork is in excellent condition for its age, the colors are period and the paper type period to its age. The piece is framed and matted and ready for display. On the right side there is a slight water stain, this could be extracted or touched up with a professional restoration I am told, however it is not in the main body of the artwork. At the bottom left is G. Morland and T. Rowlandson's credentials and on the lower right is S. Alken's credentials with the date of 1790.

This is a period piece that does not come up for sale often, it is an original and not any type of reproduction. I have no knowledge of art and only inherited this piece and only passing on the research that I have obtained. Please research online or at a local art museum for details. I am told in an auction setting this piece should sell between 1700 - 2500 USD, but I have no intrest in trying to get that as I dont even know of art gallerys around here in Kansas? 
I would like to trade this piece for a shotgun, rifle, or pistol as I am not a big art fan, I am sure there are some art enthusiest out there that would love to have it, very cool hunting scene and would display nicely. I just dont know art or what the hell to do with this piece??? So I will trade it...

Please see photos for quality, condition, size, colors, etc... Thanks so much for your time! For additional photos please email me.

title: For Trade:  1790 Pheasant Art Piece
postcontent:
You are looking at a rare piece of history here (Pheasant Shooting). This is a 1790 Brittish Aquatint that has three artist's combined works in one. The original piece was painted by George Morland English Painter (1763-1804) with permission it was Etched by Thomas Rowlandson English Painter and Caricaturist (1756-1827) and Aquatinted by Samuel Alken Sr. a Brittish Sporting Artist (1756-1815). 

This was issued as a Sporting Series in 1790 and published by J. Harris and T. Merle. This was acertained by Ralph Richardson's Chronological Catalogue of Etchings and Engravings showing their years of publication (all were published in London). Reference: http://www.sterlingtimes.org/morland_catalogue2.htm
The above link could also help reflect its value as well.

The artwork is in excellent condition for its age, the colors are period and the paper type period to its age. The piece is framed and matted and ready for display. On the right side there is a slight water stain, this could be extracted or touched up with a professional restoration I am told, however it is not in the main body of the artwork. At the bottom left is G. Morland and T. Rowlandson's credentials and on the lower right is S. Alken's credentials with the date of 1790.

This is a period piece that does not come up for sale often, it is an original and not any type of reproduction. I have no knowledge of art and only inherited this piece and only passing on the research that I have obtained. Please research online or at a local art museum for details. I am told in an auction setting this piece should sell between 1700 - 2500 USD, but I have no intrest in trying to get that as I dont even know of art gallerys around here in Kansas? 
I would like to trade this piece for a shotgun, rifle, or pistol as I am not a big art fan, I am sure there are some art enthusiest out there that would love to have it, very cool hunting scene and would display nicely. I just dont know art or what the hell to do with this piece??? So I will trade it...

Please see photos for quality, condition, size, colors, etc... Thanks so much for your time! For additional photos please email me.
